 that PCCs can cover</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="line-height:12pt; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:12pt; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">PCCs and democratically l</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">ed</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> p</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">olicing</span></p><p style="line-height:12pt; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18.31pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Bedfordshire </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">arguable </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">signposts the model for British policing in leaner times,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">as one of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the force</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> with the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> most challenging financial settlements, alongside policing challenges only seen </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">elsewhere </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">in the larger metropolitan forces.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">  Bedford</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">shire</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> was one of the first police services </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">(in 2011) </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">find insufficient police officer numbers </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">necessitated moving away from </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">model of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">neighbourhood policing model</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and today</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">same </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">challenge has led us to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">amongst the most highly collaborated services in the country.  </span></li></ol><p style="line-height:12pt; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18.31pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The decision to progress the tri-Force collaboration with Hertfordshire and Cambridgeshire </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">is</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> one which merits further consideration in relation to the democratic mandate of Commissioners. During my election campaign I stood on a platform of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">preventing wholesale outsourcing to G4S, a decision that had been made in principle by the former Police Authority, without the opportunity to test its wisdom through the crucible of public debate. However, I had the opportunity not only to access the same information that the police authority did in arriving at their decision, but to understand the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">view of the communities of Bedfordshire, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">through the face-to-face contact I had with thousands of them during my campaign, and with the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">about 200</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> of whom </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">wrote to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">me to highlight the difficulties with the planned outsourcing arrangements.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> That level of public engagement meant I was in no uncertain terms that the decision I was to take upon entering office was not only right for Bedfordshire Police, it was right for Bedfordshire.</span></li></ol><p style="line-height:12pt; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18.31pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">I would also highlight two other early decisions I took, one of which supported the stance taken by the former Police </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">A</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">uthority, and one which did not. Firstly, to increase the p</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">olice precept </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">by the maximum </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">permissible</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> amount in order to protect the local policing function, and secondly to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">overturn</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> the decision to decrease the numbers of PCSOs, and effectively maintain numbers at the levels that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">were in line with the established policing model. Again, both of these </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">decisions were taken on the basis of having undertaken significant public engagement, and based on the strong sense that the public felt Bedfordshire Police has become less visible in their communities because of d</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ifficult decisions the force had</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> take</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">n</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> in the face of funding</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> cuts.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18.31pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">There are a number of other examples I could employ to make the point about democratically led, citizen-focused policing and opening up public services that the current model of police governance allows, but I will leave it there.</span></li></ol><p style="line-height:12pt; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:12pt; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Delivering a more effective service</span></p><p style="line-height:12pt; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18.31pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">HMIC</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> recently found that</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> "the options open to Bedfordshire to deliver further savings a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">re increasingly few. While the force</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> continues to work to identify further cost savings through collaboration, there are limits to what this can deliver, and it will become ever more difficult to continue to protect frontline police officer numbers. HMIC has concerns about the force's ability to maintain its service to the public when faced with continuing funding reductions".</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">  This is </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">essentially the most pressing responsibility in my role as Police and Crime Commissioner for Bedfordshire; namely how</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, working with the Chief Constable, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">do we ensure that Bedfordshire Police continues to fight crime and safeguard the public, in a way that protects and builds public confidence, in the face of the unique crime challenges we face and with a shrinking budget</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="line-height:12pt; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18.31pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Despite HMIC’s stated view that there are limits to what collaboration can deliver, the PCCs and Chief Constables for Bedfordshire, Cambridgeshire and Hertfordshire are absolutely determined to test the limits of what can be achieved, and have – at the time of writing – just </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">signed a Memorandum of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">U</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">nderstanding that will allow all three organisations to pursue opportunities to collaborate fully on operational support and organisational support functions which include finance, fleet, estates and facilities, legal, human resources, professional standards, training, ICT, firearms licensing, custody and crime recording.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> This is in addition to the joint </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">protective </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">services currently being delivered including armed police, dogs, roads policing, major crime and scientific services.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> This collaboration will enable the three forces to make significant efficiencies whilst </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">enhancing resilience, protecting the frontline and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">maintain</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ing</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> local accountability in terms of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">local policing </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">that people value.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18.31pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">I believe this is a huge leap forward for us and represents a revolutionary shift in joint public sector working. Together joint working will help us optimi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">se all our resources</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. The journey has not been without its hiccups but</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">we’ve worked through all the obstacles to achieve unity– illustrating graphically that PCCs really are a dynamic vehicle for instigating change and progress.</span></li></ol><p style="line-height:12pt; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:12pt; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Representing</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> l</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">ocal </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">p</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">riorities</span></p><p style="line-height:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 3.3pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="10" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">As t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">he Home Affairs </span><span style="fon