n><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> me did some good work, but I am a very different beast. Bedfordshire’s </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">P</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ol</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ice </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">A</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">uthority was unique in having</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> a membership that included more women than men, and a proportion of BME members that reflected </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">our</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> community’s diversity. However, the level of engagement I undertake is in a different league. I am out and about in Bedfordshire most days</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> (including weekends)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, directly answering questions from the public at least week</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ly</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.  My </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">staff, who I inherited from the former polic</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">e authority, tell</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> me they have had more</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> op</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">portunity to undertake</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> direct public engagement in the last year than they did in the whole of the 14 years the authority existed.  </span></li></ol><p style="line-height:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="12" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Every month I personally knock on doors, telephone victims, answer questions on </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Facebook</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and via Twitter</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, speak at </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">local authority, Town and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Parish Council events and much more.  Whilst there is still more to do to raise the profile of commissioners, in Bedfordshire I am a vis</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ible form of accountability, and p</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">roactively seek out every part of the community.  I am determined that my residents will see their services protected and improved, and will use whatever mechanisms I can to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ensure this is their experience.</span></li></ol><p style="line-height:12pt; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="13" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Pounding the pavements to understand my communities in this way keeps me very busy alongside my other responsibilities.  I drive almost the entire length of my police area every day</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, although I </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">understand that what I do in Bedfordsh</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ire, will be impossible </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">for </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">those PCC</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s who have larger geographies. Part of the ‘added value’ for PCCs is the local factor.  Policing has always had a level of political control, but PCCs </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">are a critical part of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">provid</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ing</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> a local balance against the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">national role of the Home Secretary who cannot begin to reflect the diverse policing needs of different parts of the country.</span></li></ol><p style="line-height:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="14" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In addition to engaging and listening to the people of Bedfordshire, I have also taken steps to formalise issues raised as part of my Police and Crime Plan. In my first year I have run over a dozen ‘roundtable’ events – with single topic agendas bringing together residents, community and voluntary groups and statutory practitioners to discuss key issues like rural and wildlife crime, business crime, hate crime, serious youth violence and volunteering.</span></li></ol><p style="line-height:12pt; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:12pt; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Promoting Confident Communities</span></p><p style="line-height:12pt; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#