ont-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">’</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> services from October 2014.  During my first year the number of police referrals to victim services has significantly increased, as has the satisfaction of victims with Bedfordshire Police.  I am determined to see this continue, and personally telephone victims of crime to hear about the services they received from partners right across the system. I am a new and important voice for these victims</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, and my direct engagement with them offers a new perspective in the meetings I have with </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">heads of local services, including as a full member of Bedfordshire’s Criminal Justice Board.</span></li></ol><p style="line-height:12pt; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="24" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">For PCC</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">to make a significant </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">difference </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">on </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">crime levels</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, we must not operate in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">our </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">policing silos, but work in strong partnership with other community safety and crime reduction agencies.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> As we all know, the underlying causes of crime include alcohol and drug misuse, unmet mental health needs, childhood trauma and much more. Whilst </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">PCCs</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> do not have the resources to deal with these issues we must make sure that preventative services provided by partners are cohesive and effective. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="25" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">My contribution has been to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">provide</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> significant funding for a multi-agency scheme to tackle the revolving door of re-offending</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, increasing the offenders in the scheme by </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">over two-thirds</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> On taking office I</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> was immediately impressed with the highly effective Integrated Offender Management (IOM) scheme that Bedfordshire has and its success in reducing harm, backed by evidence based evaluations that had been undertaken. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">PCCs have the independence they need to support similar evidence based schemes to help embed cultures of efficiency and effect</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">iveness right across the system.</span></li></ol><p style="line-height:12pt; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="26" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">I have also shown that PCCs can not only initiate change through commissioning, but by bring people together. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">With the Directors of Public Health I have set up a group designed to tackle the healthcare needs of offenders, thereby reducing costs across the public sector. Working with Bedfordshire Probation, the Force and local Public Health I am keen to re-commission the Drugs Intervention Programme to ensure it remains fit for purpose in helping offenders </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">break their drug taking habits.  More broadly, I have</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">also </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">introduced a countywide Demand Reduction Board to help public sector agencies align their activity toward shared </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">objectives and outcomes and it is through this forum that I intend to deliver much of the ‘Preventing Crime’ ambition set out in the Police and Crime Plan.</span></li></ol><p style="line-height:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:12pt; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Collaboration with other Police and Crime Commissioners</span></p><p style="line-height:12pt; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="27" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">There is too much duplication across the police service</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, and Bedfordshire has done a great deal to collaborate specialist and business functions with two other forces, and Serious and Organised Crime capabilities across six forces.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">HMIC have praised our collaboration saying there is very few opportunities left</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> to reduce </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">spending </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">without impacting on the frontline</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">  </span></li></ol><p style="line-height:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="28" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">My work on progressing collaboration does have occasional setbacks, but </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">I have found every commissioner I have worked with to be</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> positive and forward looking. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">  Collaboration is how I deliver against the Strategic Policing Requirement and protect the visible local policing </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">communities ask me to provide.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">  Police Professional recently described our advanced position as “unique for bringing together such a wide range of [services] under a three-force rather than two-force approach”.  </span></li></ol><p style="line-height:12pt; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="29" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Bedfordshire has also led the way on much wider collaboration between PCCs.  Last year 600,000 crimes were committed by those who had offended before and nearly half of those released from prison go on to re-offend, in many cases not just once but time and again. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Knowing that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">a solution that would help rehabilitate offenders and reduce the number of victims was available but blocked by the existing Ministry of Justice</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">’s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> National</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> Electronic Monitoring Contract, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">I worked with 26 other</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> PCCs </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">of all </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">political </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">shades to raise this issue with the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Justice </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Secretary</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. </span></li></ol><p style="line-height:12pt; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="30" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">This was the first occasion on which </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">commissioners</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> came together to lobby the government. It was quite an achievement at </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">an early point in our</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> relationship </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">and points to further opportunities in the future.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">There is far more that unites than divide</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s PCCs</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, particularly the growing realisation that all too often it is what Whitehall does or does not do that frustrates us. This is not a party political point but a fact of life to which many of our more established partners in criminal justice and beyond can attest.</span></li></ol><p style="line-height:12pt; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="31" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">PC</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">C</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s can be the catalyst for change, and furthermore they can be the hub that brings people together for action. With tagging we have support from all sides – police, probation, community safety partners, local authorities, the judiciary and offenders and ex-offenders themselves. Locally, if we were able to add Central Government to this list, we would be able to deliver further significant reductions in offending and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">victimisation.</span></li></ol><p style="line-height:12pt; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="32" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">I understand that when the former Policing Minister</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, Rt Hon. member for Arundel and South Downs (Mr Nick Herbert)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> was developing the concept of PCCs he considered calling them Police and Justice Commissioners. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">This in my view would have been appropriate because t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">he value of PCCs in their first year has not been to tinker with different bits of the police service, as i</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">mportant as it is to ensure the police</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> are focused on the needs of the public, but </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">to make real </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">progress towards realising the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">opportunities </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">that</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> deliver</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ing</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> the system wide reform which </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">we desperately need</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="line-height:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:12pt; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Declaration of Interest as requested for Written Submissions can be found at </span><a href="http://www.bedfordshire.pcc.police.uk/wp-content/uploads/2013/10/REGISTER-OF-INTERESTS-PCC-amended-250213.pdf"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.bedfordshire.pcc.police.uk/wp-content/uploads/2013/10/REGISTER-OF-INTERESTS-PCC-amended-250213.pdf</span></a></p><p style="line-height:11pt; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:12pt; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:12pt; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Olly Martins </span></p><p style="line-height:12pt; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Police and Crime Commissioner for Bedfordshire</span></p><p style="line-height:12pt; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">December 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">7</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>